    "body_text": [
        {
            "endOffset": 244521,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "In scheduling problems with multiple machines there can be additional constraints that do not allow some job\u2013machine pairs.",
            "startOffset": 244398,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 266908,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "s000020",
                    "title": "Some properties of nearly Monge matrices with incompatible partner indices"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "s000025",
            "sentence": "Models of this type arise for example in the scheduling context.",
            "startOffset": 266844,
            "title": "Nonexistence of a Monge sequence"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 267020,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "s000020",
                    "title": "Some properties of nearly Monge matrices with incompatible partner indices"
                }
            ],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br000080": {
                    "endOffset": 266952,
                    "startOffset": 266945
                },
                "br000085": {
                    "endOffset": 266952,
                    "startOffset": 266945
                }
            },
            "secId": "s000025",
            "sentence": "The scheduling problems studied in  [16,17]  can be modeled as transportation problems with non-Monge matrices.",
            "startOffset": 266909,
            "title": "Nonexistence of a Monge sequence"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 266843,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "s000020",
                    "title": "Some properties of nearly Monge matrices with incompatible partner indices"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "s000025",
            "sentence": "A Monge sequence, if one exists, is a powerful tool for solving problems with matrices which do not satisfy the Monge property for all quadruples.",
            "startOffset": 266697,
            "title": "Nonexistence of a Monge sequence"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 267267,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "s000020",
                    "title": "Some properties of nearly Monge matrices with incompatible partner indices"
                }
            ],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br000085": {
                    "endOffset": 267266,
                    "startOffset": 267262
                }
            },
            "secId": "s000025",
            "sentence": "In some cases Monge sequences can be found efficiently; in others a Monge sequence does not exist, and this calls for a development of special tailor-made algorithms, as in the case of the generalized (weighted) version of the problem from  [17].",
            "startOffset": 267021,
            "title": "Nonexistence of a Monge sequence"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 244873,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "Assignment problems with nearly Monge arrays defined by incompatible partners arise for example in applications related to satellite communication or in synchronous open shop scheduling.",
            "startOffset": 244687,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 292544,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000050",
            "sentence": "We discuss these two results in Sections 7.1\u20137.2.",
            "startOffset": 292495,
            "title": "The corridor property for other versions of the assignment problem"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 244158,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "For example, in timetabling the allocation of certain classes to some classrooms or time slots has to be avoided.",
            "startOffset": 244045,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 292589,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000050",
            "sentence": "Both problems deal with a min-sum objective.",
            "startOffset": 292545,
            "title": "The corridor property for other versions of the assignment problem"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 292494,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000050",
            "sentence": "In the literature, a property of this type was established, for example, for the three-dimensional assignment problem with decomposable costs and for the planar 3-dimensional assignment problem.",
            "startOffset": 292300,
            "title": "The corridor property for other versions of the assignment problem"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 244397,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "In scheduling problems with unit processing times and arbitrary release dates and deadlines (which can be modeled as an assignment problem), it is not allowed to allocate a job to a time slot before its release date or after its deadline.",
            "startOffset": 244159,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 265412,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000015",
            "sentence": "The complexity results discussed in this section are summarized in  Table 1 in the Conclusions.",
            "startOffset": 265317,
            "title": "NP-hardness of problem AP(d,\u03bb)"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 291983,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br000025": {
                    "endOffset": 291964,
                    "startOffset": 291961
                },
                "br000030": {
                    "endOffset": 291981,
                    "startOffset": 291978
                }
            },
            "secId": "s000045",
            "sentence": "The maximization problem of type (ii) with a nearly Monge weight array is no easier than the version of the same problem with a Monge array; the latter problem is known to be NP-hard (see  [5], p. 132, or  [6]).",
            "startOffset": 291772,
            "title": "A linear-time algorithm for problem AP(d,\u03bb) with fixed d and \u03bb"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 244044,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "Applications of assignment problems with incompatible partners are typical for scenarios where items from different sets have to be matched, but there is a certain number of combinations that are forbidden.",
            "startOffset": 243838,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 292299,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000050",
            "sentence": "The corridor property that characterizes the structure of an optimal solution and restricts the search to entries around the diagonal, also holds for other versions of the assignment problem.",
            "startOffset": 292108,
            "title": "The corridor property for other versions of the assignment problem"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 245101,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "We discuss the two applications in more detail in Section  2 and the relation to max-weight edge coloring in Section  3.",
            "startOffset": 244981,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 292041,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br000030": {
                    "endOffset": 292005,
                    "startOffset": 292002
                }
            },
            "secId": "s000045",
            "sentence": "The results from  [6] are also discussed in Section  7.1.",
            "startOffset": 291984,
            "title": "A linear-time algorithm for problem AP(d,\u03bb) with fixed d and \u03bb"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 244687,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "In transportation scheduling, allocations of certain types of vehicles to some routes can be forbidden; in addition there may be restrictions on drivers\u2019 allocation.",
            "startOffset": 244522,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 292775,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000050",
            "sentence": "An alternative version, known as the bottleneck assignment problem, deals with a min\u2013max objective; we generalize our results for that version of the assignment problem in Section  7.3.",
            "startOffset": 292590,
            "title": "The corridor property for other versions of the assignment problem"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 244980,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "s000005",
            "sentence": "There also exists a close relation to the well-known max-weight edge coloring problem on bipartite graphs.",
            "startOffset": 244874,
            "title": "Introduction"
        }
    ],
